Practical Machine Learning Predictions

using HAR weight lifting dataset

John Rusnak

November 2, 2016

Synopsis

Per the final project page,using devices such as Jawbone Up, Nike FuelBand, and Fitbit it is now possible to collect a large amount of data about personal activity relatively inexpensively. One thing that people regularly do is quantify how much of a particular activity they do, but they rarely quantify how well they do it. Six young health participants were asked to perform one set of 10 repetitions of the Unilateral Dumbbell Biceps Curl in five different fashions: exactly according to the specification (Class A), throwing the elbows to the front (Class B), lifting the dumbbell only halfway (Class C), lowering the dumbbell only halfway (Class D) and throwing the hips to the front (Class E). The goal of this project was to predict the manner in which they did the exercise. This is the “classe” variable in the training set.

After some data cleansing and “tidying up”.we will investigate the accuracy of using two models, each utilizing cross validation with 2 K-folds, in predicting the values of the “classe” variable. The first approach used rpart to develop a classification tree and was minimally accurate at 50%. Much greater accuracy was achieved using a random forest approach which resulted in 99% accuracy.

Loading the required files, libraries used and preparing the data files for analysis

Load libraries and data files

library(caret)
library(ggplot2)
library(rattle)

The data for this project come from this source: http://groupware.les.inf.puc-rio.br/har. If you use the document you create for this class for any purpose please cite them as they have been very generous in allowing their data to be used for this kind of assignment. The training data for this project are available here: https://d396qusza40orc.cloudfront.net/predmachlearn/pml-training.csv The test data are available here: https://d396qusza40orc.cloudfront.net/predmachlearn/pml-testing.csv The following code downloads the csv files and reads them into the train and testing data frames.

url1<-"https://d396qusza40orc.cloudfront.net/predmachlearn/pml-training.csv"
url2<-"https://d396qusza40orc.cloudfront.net/predmachlearn/pml-testing.csv"
download.file(url1,destfile="pml-training.csv",method="curl")
download.file(url2,destfile="pml-testing.csv",method="curl")
train<-read.csv("pml-training.csv",na.strings=c("NA",""),stringsAsFactors=F)
testing<-read.csv("pml-testing.csv",na.strings=c("NA",""),stringsAsFactors=F)

Preparing the train data frame for analysis

We confirm that the train and testing data frames have the same potential predictor variables. We see that only train contains the “classe” variable, while only testing contains the “problem_id”. All other predictor variables are in both. So all is good.

setdiff(names(train),names(testing))
## [1] "classe"
setdiff(names(testing),names(train))
## [1] "problem_id"

We will now cleanup the train data frame. First we will remove the first seven variables, such as obs #,user name and time stamps,etc. These variables do not contribute to predicting classe. Second, we remove the variables with near zero variance. These variables also do not contribute to explaining or predicting the classe variable.

train<-train[,-(1:7)] 
nzv<-nearZeroVar(train)
train<-train[, -nzv]

Now we will look at variables where the majority of observation as NA.

NAcolsum<-apply(train,2,function(x) sum(is.na(x)))
table(NAcolsum)
## NAcolsum
##     0 19216 
##    53    58

We see that there are 53 variables with no NAs and 58 variables where 19216,out of 19622 rows, are NA. We will keep the 53 variables with no NAs. and call the resulting data frame trainfinal.

NAcolsum<-apply(train,2,function(x) sum(is.na(x))==0)
trainfinal<-train[,NAcolsum]

Partition the trainfinal data frame into training and training validation data frames.

set.seed(246810)
inTrain = createDataPartition(trainfinal$classe, p = 0.7,list=F)
training = trainfinal[ inTrain,]
testval = trainfinal[-inTrain,]
training$classe<-as.factor(training$classe)
testval$classe<-as.factor(testval$classe)

The testing data frame does not include the classe variable since it will be used for the prediction quiz as part of this project. So we randomly partition the trainfinal data frame into training(training) and testing(testval) using the createDataPartition on the classe variable with a 70/30 split. We then set the classe variable in each df as a factor. Lets look at the proportion of the classe variable in each data frame using the prop.table function. We see that performing the exercise exactly to specification(A) occurs about 28% while the other 4 are in the 16% to 19% range.

round(prop.table(table(training$classe)),2)
## 
##    A    B    C    D    E 
## 0.28 0.19 0.17 0.16 0.18
round(prop.table(table(testval$classe)),2)
## 
##    A    B    C    D    E 
## 0.28 0.19 0.17 0.16 0.18

Model prediction methodology, accuracy analysis and preparing testing data frame for predictions

Given the categorical nature of the classe variable, it seems natural to investigate the use of classification prediction models such as decision trees(will use rpart) and ensemble of tress(will use the random forest package). Each modelling methodology will include the use of a 2 k-fold cross validation process in an effort to reduce variability. Each of the two cross validation partitions will alternately be used for training and testing the model and the validation results are averaged over the rounds. Lets use rpart to model a decision tree and view the decision tree using the following code:

modfit<-train(classe ~ .,method="rpart",data=training,
              trControl=trainControl(method="cv",number=2))
## Loading required package: rpart
fancyRpartPlot(modfit$finalModel)

Figure 1: Decision Tree using rpart

The tree shows roll_belt,pitch_forearm,and magnet_dumbbell_y,etc as the important predictor variables. Time to check accuracy of the model on the testval data frame.

confusionMatrix(testval$classe,predict(modfit,testval))$table
##           Reference
## Prediction    A    B    C    D    E
##          A 1513   36  118    0    7
##          B  460  417  262    0    0
##          C  455   44  527    0    0
##          D  429  205  330    0    0
##          E  151  153  297    0  481
confusionMatrix(testval$classe,predict(modfit,testval))$overall[1]
##  Accuracy 
## 0.4992353

We see that overall accuracy is only about 49%. With accuracy at such a low level, lets move on to predicting with an ensemble of trees using the random forest package. Lets generate the model and check accuracy. Again because of processing time on my old Mac laptop,I’m going to limit the number of trees to 11 instead of the default of 500.

rf_model<-train(classe ~ .,data=training,method='rf',ntree=11,importance=T,
                        trControl=trainControl(method="cv",number=2))
## Loading required package: randomForest
## Warning: package 'randomForest' was built under R version 3.2.3
## randomForest 4.6-12
## Type rfNews() to see new features/changes/bug fixes.
## 
## Attaching package: 'randomForest'
## The following object is masked from 'package:ggplot2':
## 
##     margin
confusionMatrix(testval$classe,predict(rf_model,testval))$table
##           Reference
## Prediction    A    B    C    D    E
##          A 1667    2    1    1    3
##          B   17 1111    9    1    1
##          C    0   14 1007    5    0
##          D    0    2   10  950    2
##          E    0    3    2    9 1068
acc<-confusionMatrix(testval$classe,predict(rf_model,testval))$overall
acc
##       Accuracy          Kappa  AccuracyLower  AccuracyUpper   AccuracyNull 
##    0.986066270    0.982371933    0.982733704    0.988903164    0.286321155 
## AccuracyPValue  McnemarPValue 
##    0.000000000    0.000638265

We see that accuracy has tremendously improved to almost 99% with 11 trees using only a 2 k-fold cross validation! Lets look at this model in a little bit more detail. First we’ll plot the model rf_model

plot(rf_model)

Figure 2: Optimal Predictor Values

We see that cross-validation accuracy peaked at using 27 out of the 52 potential predictors. Lets look at the top 10 predictors.

plot(varImp(rf_model),top=10)

Figure 3: Top 10 Predictor Variables by Classe

The variable roll_belt appears to be the top predictor for each classe except for classe=C. A violin plot for roll_belt appears below where the black dot is the mean value of roll_belt for that classe. The means are different for each classe but the patterns of the probability density are similar.

ggplot(training,aes(x=classe,y=roll_belt)) + 
        geom_violin(aes(color=classe,fill=classe)) + 
        stat_summary(fun.y=mean,geom="point",size=2,color="black")

Figure 4: Violin Plot for roll_belt

Out of sample error rate estimate

Reminder the accuracy of the rf_model was as follows

acc
##       Accuracy          Kappa  AccuracyLower  AccuracyUpper   AccuracyNull 
##    0.986066270    0.982371933    0.982733704    0.988903164    0.286321155

Based on the above accuracy results for the random forest model on the testval data we would expect our out of sample error rate to be between 1.11% and 1.73%

Prepare testing data frame for quiz predictions

The quiz portion of the final project entails predicting the classe value for the testing data frame. We will make the predictions using the random forest model rf_model. First we must make the same adjustments to the testing data frame that we made to the training data frame which was used to train the model.

  1. Remove variable not needed
testing<-testing[,-(1:7)]
  1. Remove the same near zero variance columns that were removed from training
testing<-testing[, -nzv]
  1. Remove the same columns that were mostly NA in training
testing<-testing[,NAcolsum]

As earlier, lets use setdiff to check all columns that same except for classe and problem_id

setdiff(names(training),names(testing))
## [1] "classe"
setdiff(names(testing),names(training))
## [1] "problem_id"

Classe predictions for quiz using the testing data frame and rf_model.

predict(rf_model,newdata=testing)
##  [1] B A B A A E D B A A B C B A E E A B B B
## Levels: A B C D E

Conclusions

This was a good assignment that put into practice some of the methodologies of statistical inference learned in the course. The analysis showed,with 95% confidence, that vitamin c did have a positive impact on tooth growth in guinea pigs with impact increasing as the dose increased except as noted and in general the supplement method of OJ outperformed that of ascorbic acid(VC),except for the 2.0 dosage.
